{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 administration, faculty, and students have openly expressed their disapproval with the military\rquote s policy in a variety of ways. Some law schools, for example, have posted ameliorative statements throughout the school advising that the military does not comply with the school\rquote s non-discrimination policies.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (Appleton Decl. \u182\'3f 18, Ex. 9; Law Decl. \u182\'3f 22). Law faculty and student bar resolutions also have condemned the military\rquote s policy and, correspondingly, expressed support of non-discrimination policies. (Appleton Decl. \u182\'3f\u182\'3f 14, 16; Law Decl. \u182\'3f\u182\'3f 22\u8211\'3f23). In addition, students and faculty have held demonstrations protesting on-campus military recruiting. (Appleton Decl. \u182\'3f 19; Gerken Decl. \u182\'3f\u182\'3f 24\u8211\'3f28; Law Decl. \u182\'3f 35, Smolik Decl. \u182\'3f 2; Sweeney Decl. \u182\'3f 11).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Law schools have attempted to comply with the Solomon Amendment, notwithstanding the military\rquote s discriminatory policy. While some law schools denied military access to campus, others developed ways to adhere to their respective non-discrimination policies and still permit the military access to interested students. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f\u182\'3f 7(j),(k)). Some law schools permitted the military to recruit on campus, but refused to schedule student interviews. (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Id.
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u182\'3f 7(k)). Other law schools allowed military recruiters to use university facilities, but not law school facilities. (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Id.
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
). Many refused to let military recruiters participate in school-sponsored job fairs. (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Id.
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
). Still other schools refused to match students with recruiters or post military literature. (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Id.
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 \u182\'3f 34). One law school, for example, allowed military recruiters on campus, but kept military recruiting literature separate from its career services office and arranged interviews through the dean\rquote s office. (Rosenkranz Decl. \u182\'3f 19).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
On occasion, the military has expressed satisfaction with the law schools\rquote  efforts to accommodate military recruiters. For instance, a 1998 letter from the Department of the Army thanked USC Law\rquote s career services office \u8220\'3ffor providing ... military recruiters a degree of access to students that is equal in quality and scope to that afforded other employers, consistent with the regulations....\u8221\'3f (Chemerinsky Decl. \u182\'3f 19). Another 1998 letter from the Department of the Army thanked NYU Law for its efforts in notifying students about a military recruiter\rquote s scheduled trip to the New York area. (Law Decl. \u182\'3f 16; Ex. 6). That same letter signaled an abundance of recruits, stating that \u8220\'3f[c]ompetition has become very keen in the past few years for ... JAG attorney positions\u8221\'3f and that, as a result, \u8220\'3fsome very qualified applicants will not be selected for a position.\u8221\'3f (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Id.
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
However, in or about 2001, the military began to express dissatisfaction with the law schools. The DOD and officers of various branches of the military notified various schools that they were not in compliance with the Solomon Amendment. Plaintiffs have submitted detailed declarations recounting Solomon Amendment stories from at least nine different law schools. In general, Plaintiffs allege that the DOD threatened law schools with the loss of not only DOD funding, but all federal funding, if the schools did not afford the military full access to career services, the students, and the law schools. (Am. Compl. \u182\'3f 36; Chemerinsky Decl. \u182\'3f 21; Gerken Decl. \u182\'3f 16). Plaintiffs further allege that, despite written requests from various law schools, the DOD failed to 
}
