{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 are illustrative of the DOD\rquote s current stance. Yale Law School consistently permitted military recruiters on campus to meet students in response to expressed student interest, and provided military recruiters access to student directory information.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (Eskridge Decl. \u182\'3f\u182\'3f 37, 40). But the school-sponsored off-campus interview programs were only open to employers that complied with the school\rquote s non-discrimination policy. (Eskridge Decl. \u182\'3f 40). By letter dated May 29, 2002, United States Army Colonel Tate notified Yale that the Law School was non-compliant with the Solomon Amendment insofar as it (1) maintained a policy that limited military recruiting; (2) did not provide the military access to law school-sponsored interviewing programs; and (3) did not permit the military to recruit on campus unless invited on by a law student or law student organization. (Eskridge Decl. \u182\'3f 41, Ex. 10). The letter threatened funding denial unless, by July 1, 2002, the Army received information that the law school had modified its policies to conform to federal requirements. (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Id.
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
). By letter dated May 29, 2003, Acting Deputy Under Secretary of Defense William Carr notified Yale that allowing military recruiters to use law school facilities, but not the career development office, violated the Solomon Amendment because the DOD had interpreted the statute \u8220\'3fto require universities to provide military recruiters access to students equal in quality and scope to that provided to other recruiters.\u8221\'3f (Eskridge Decl. \u182\'3f 55; Ex. 18). According to Mr. Carr, not allowing the military access to the law school\rquote s career development services would \u8220\'3fimpose substantial burdens and restrictions ... to schedule interviews with students through e-mail or other means, rather than through the standard processes provided ... to other employers.\u8221\'3f (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Id.
}
