 was grappling with whether the plaintiff association had any members who had standing in their own right. That is not the case here. Plaintiffs\rquote  allegations and sworn declarations are sufficient to demonstrate that FAIR\rquote s members have suffered harm sufficient to confer standing in their own right. The Government\rquote s argument places undue emphasis on language requiring plaintiff associations to \u8220\'3fidentify\u8221\'3f or \u8220\'3fname\u8221\'3f members. Such language in the cited authorities goes not to a blanket rule that associations seeking to bring suit on behalf of their members must identify their membership, but rather to whether the factual allegations in a given context sufficiently demonstrate that an association indeed has members that have suffered an injury-in-fact.
