{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Only schools whose policies or practices \u8220\'3fprohibit [ed], or in effect prevent[ed],\u8221\'3f military representatives \u8220\'3ffrom gaining entry to campuses, or access to students ... on campuses for purposes of military recruiting,\u8221\'3f were penalized. Thus, by merely allowing military recruiters to gain access to campuses, many law schools avoided the Solomon Amendment\rquote s penalty while reaffirming their opposition to the military\rquote s exclusionary employment policy by not providing them affirmative assistance in the manner provided to other recruiters. Harvard Law School, for example, allowed military recruiters on campus to recruit at the offices of its Veterans Association but did not volunteer its placement personnel to arrange interviews. Boston College Law School allowed military recruiters to conduct on-campus interviews, but kept their literature in the library rather than in the career services office. Until the fall of 2001, the DOD did not consider these and other similar \u8220\'3fameliorative measures\u8221\'3f to violate the Solomon Amendment and expressed enthusiasm for the law schools\rquote  cooperation with what it described as successful recruiting efforts. 
