{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The District Court rejected FAIR\rquote s argument and held that the law schools are not compelled to express a particular ideological message by admitting and actively assisting the military recruiters.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 We disagree. As we explain in the analysis that follows, the military\rquote s recruiting is expressive of a message with which the law schools disagree. To comply with the Solomon Amendment, the law schools must affirmatively assist military recruiters in the same manner they assist other recruiters, which means they must propagate, accommodate, and subsidize the military\rquote s message. In so doing, the Solomon Amendment conditions funding on a basis that violates the law schools\rquote  First Amendment rights under the compelled speech doctrine.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
