In this case, the law schools portray their efforts to keep military recruiters off their campuses as \u8220\'3fquintessential expression.\u8221\'3f (Appellant br. at 20.) But when an institution excludes military recruiters from its campuses or otherwise restricts their access to students, it is engaging in something different from \u8220\'3fquintessential expression.\u8221\'3f It is engaging in a course of conduct which contains both nonspeech and speech elements. The acts which the law schools claim they are compelled to do by virtue of the military\rquote s post\u8212\'3f2001 \u8220\'3funwritten policy\u8221\'3f\u8212\'3fdisseminating and posting military recruitment literature, making appointments for military recruiters to meet with students and providing military recruiters a place to meet with students\u8212\'3falso contain both nonspeech and speech elements.
