Law schools have determined that diversity among their faculty and students is essential to their core mission of \u8220\'3ftrain[ing] the next generation of leaders to pursue justice, respect the rule of law, and stand by principle.\u8221\'3f (Am.Com pl.\u182\'3f\u182\'3f 19\u8211\'3f21) (\u8220\'3f[L]aw schools have promoted, demanded, and strictly enforced, not merely diversity, but also tolerance and respect.\u8221\'3f). Nearly every accredited American law school has adopted policies against discrimination on the basis of categories such as national origin, religion, gender, race, ethnicity, marital status, parental status, veteran status, physical disability, age, and sexual orientation. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f\u182\'3f 21\u8211\'3f22). Law schools admit students, award scholarships, hire and promote faculty, and hire staff consistent with their non-discrimination policies. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f 23). A typical law school non-discrimination policy states:
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
[The Law School] is committed to a policy against discrimination based upon age, color, handicap or disability, ethnic or national origin, race, religion, religious creed, gender (including discrimination taking the form of sexual harassment), marital, parental or veteran status, or sexual orientation.
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
(Am.Compl.\u182\'3f 22). The trend of including sexual orientation as a protected category in non-discrimination policies began in the late 1970s. NYU Law was the first school to do so, and others followed its lead. (Rosenkranz Decl. \u182\'3f 10).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
As corollaries to their non-discrimination policies, law schools adhere to recruiting policies whereby they refuse to offer school resources, support, or endorsement to any employer that discriminates based on protected categories. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f 23). The recruitment policies are applied even-handedly to all employers. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f 26). The policies, in the law schools\rquote  judgment, serve both pedagogical and instrumental purposes by teaching values students would not otherwise learn from case books and by fostering an environment of free and open discourse. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f\u182\'3f 24\u8211\'3f25). The policies neither prevent discriminating employers from contacting students, nor steer students away from such employers. While students remain free to seek jobs with employers that discriminate, including the military, they must do so without school support or resources. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f 26).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
