 (Eskridge Decl. \u182\'3f\u182\'3f 37, 40). But the school-sponsored off-campus interview programs were only open to employers that complied with the school\rquote s non-discrimination policy. (Eskridge Decl. \u182\'3f 40). By letter dated May 29, 2002, United States Army Colonel Tate notified Yale that the Law School was non-compliant with the Solomon Amendment insofar as it (1) maintained a policy that limited military recruiting; (2) did not provide the military access to law school-sponsored interviewing programs; and (3) did not permit the military to recruit on campus unless invited on by a law student or law student organization. (Eskridge Decl. \u182\'3f 41, Ex. 10). The letter threatened funding denial unless, by July 1, 2002, the Army received information that the law school had modified its policies to conform to federal requirements. (
