The Government further argues that FAIR members lack standing because the decision to comply with the Solomon Amendment was not made by the law schools, alone, but by their parent institutions. The Court disagrees. Plaintiffs\rquote  Second Amended Complaint specifically alleges that \u8220\'3f[a]s a direct result of the Solomon Amendment, or the DOD\rquote s interpretation and application of the Solomon Amendment, every FAIR member has entirely suspended the application of its non-discrimination policy to military recruiters.\u8221\'3f (Am Compl. \u182\'3f 7(h)). The decision to suspend the non-discrimination policies, even if at the direction of a parent university, was made in direct response to the Solomon Amendment. In any event, the vast majority of law schools that suspended their policies did so by vote of the law school faculty. (Rosenkranz Decl. Opp\rquote n Gov\rquote t 2nd Mot. to Dismiss \u182\'3f 6).
\par 
