SALT is an organization of law professors from various law schools throughout the nation. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f 8). The law schools where SALT members teach have implemented non-discrimination policies that allow law professors to \u8220\'3fpursue scholarly goals and prepare their students for the practice of law in an atmosphere that encourages debate, celebrates diversity and promotes the ideals of respect and tolerance within their communities.\u8221\'3f (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f\u182\'3f 8(a),(b)). Plaintiffs allege that SALT members are \u8220\'3fboth beneficiaries and recipients of the messages of non-discrimination sent by the policies and they are harmed by their respective law schools\rquote  suspension of\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 those policies. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f 8(e)). The alleged injury to SALT members is that, due to the Solomon Amendment, they are unable to benefit from the enriched pedagogical environment created by non-discrimination policies. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f\u182\'3f 8(c)-(e)). SALT members who were instrumental in the development and implementation of non-discrimination policies at their respective law schools claim an additional injury of no longer being able to send their schools\rquote  message free from interference due to the Solomon Amendment. (Am.Compl.\u182\'3f (f)). In short, SALT members claim that they are being denied \u8220\'3fthe fulfillment of [their] educational mission and the meaningful exercise of [their] own rights of academic freedom.\u8221\'3f (Johnson Reply Decl. \u182\'3f 7).
\par 
}
