 Conditioning receipt of federal funds upon an educational institution\rquote s willingness to assist the military\rquote s recruiting efforts involves a less serious infringement upon First Amendment liberties than compelling the affirmative act of a flag salute or even the passive act of carrying the state motto on one\rquote s license plate. Facilitating interviews and even disseminating recruiting literature on behalf of military recruiters, when a law school does all these things for every other potential employer in the context of a large recruiting function, are not obvious endorsements of a particular ideological point of view. The Court therefore rejects Plaintiffs\rquote  contention that the Solomon Amendment requires law schools to endorse the military\rquote s recruiting \u8216\'3fmessage.\u8217\'3f
