{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 to require that there not \u8220\'3fbe a substantial disparity in the treatment of military recruiters as compared to other potential employers\u8221\'3f and that the statute \u8220\'3fshould, and will, be construed to require equal access for military recruiters\u8212\'3fthe construction that better permits the military to fulfill congressional intent.\u8221\'3f That interpretation of the Solomon Amendment is problematic for several reasons. Insisting on \u8220\'3fequal access\u8221\'3f and demanding that there be no \u8220\'3fsubstantial disparity\u8221\'3f are not the same thing. No substantial disparity allows for something less than equal access. More importantly, the statute could easily have provided that military recruiters are to be treated the same as other employers. The statute does not so provide. While it is conceivable (in presently unknown circumstances) that a substantial disparity between treatment of the military and other employers could rise to the level of \u8220\'3fin effect prevent[ing]\u8221\'3f military recruitment efforts, the Court simply fails to see how the statute requires absolute parity when all that it requires is that a school not \u8220\'3fprohibit\u8221\'3f or \u8220\'3fin effect prevent\u8221\'3f military recruiting efforts. Finally, reading the \u8220\'3fequal in quality and scope\u8221\'3f aspect into the substantive statutory requirements swallows the exemption for schools allowing a \u8220\'3fdegree of access by military recruiters [that] is at least equal in quality and scope to that afforded to other employers,\u8221\'3f 
}
